00:02:12.070 --> 00:02:17.700 position:56%
We'd like to know how the program
-- what you liked about the program.

00:02:17.700 --> 00:02:21.100
And you can leave these
forms at the reference desk

00:02:21.100 --> 00:02:23.790 position:56%
at the back in the little container.

00:02:23.790 --> 00:02:28.250
And we'd also like to invite you
to ask questions during our program

00:02:28.250 --> 00:02:32.460
after this, but this
program is being videotaped.

00:02:32.460 --> 00:02:37.570
So if you ask questions you're
implicitly giving your permission

00:02:37.570 --> 00:02:40.700
for us to be recorded.

00:02:40.700 --> 00:02:43.430
Now I'd like to introduce
our speaker.

00:02:43.430 --> 00:02:48.130
Guy Burak is the Middle Eastern
and Islamic studies librarian

00:02:48.130 --> 00:02:52.310
at New York University,
Elmer Holmes Library.

00:02:52.310 --> 00:02:56.770
He is the author of The Second
Formation of Islamic Law,

00:02:56.770 --> 00:03:00.740
it was published by Cambridge
University Press in 2015.

00:03:00.740 --> 00:03:05.750
And he publishes regularly on
Ottoman and Islamic history.

00:03:05.750 --> 00:03:11.030
He did his PhD at NYU on
Ottoman legal history and was

00:03:11.030 --> 00:03:16.140
in the Islamic legal studies
program at Harvard University.

00:03:16.140 --> 00:03:21.420 position:56%
He began working at NYU on February
2013, so he's a relatively newcomer.

00:03:21.420 --> 00:03:26.520 position:56%
But he seems to do it all reference,
acquisitions, and cataloging.

00:03:26.520 --> 00:03:31.530
And one of his many projects at NYU

00:03:31.530 --> 00:03:36.650 position:56%
and his most recent endeavors
involves cataloguing the Abdul Hamid

00:03:36.650 --> 00:03:39.120
collections at NYU.

00:03:39.120 --> 00:03:43.620
And this is a very special
collection that was presented

00:03:43.620 --> 00:03:48.340
by Abram Hewitt to the
Library of Congress.

00:03:48.340 --> 00:03:53.420
We've got over almost 400
books, it has also been a gift

00:03:53.420 --> 00:03:58.350
to the British Library, as
well as to New York University.

00:03:58.350 --> 00:04:01.890
So without further ado I'll
let Guy Barak tell us all

00:04:01.890 --> 00:04:04.050
about that collection
and his work with it.

00:04:04.050 --> 00:04:05.380
Thank you.

00:04:05.380 --> 00:04:12.070
&gt;&gt; Guy Burak: And good afternoon,
I have notes but I just speak.

00:04:12.070 --> 00:04:15.770
And thank you Joan for the
invitation to be here, to talk

00:04:15.770 --> 00:04:18.930
and share with you and my
experience with this project.

00:04:18.930 --> 00:04:23.740
And it has been and it is a real
pleasure to be at the Library

00:04:23.740 --> 00:04:27.410
of Congress in general and
specifically to be here

00:04:27.410 --> 00:04:36.000
with this project that I have
been working on for quite a while.

00:04:36.000 --> 00:04:40.660
And it's very much a work
in progress and I hope

00:04:40.660 --> 00:04:44.920
that it will be the beginning
of a conversation between NYU

00:04:44.920 --> 00:04:47.960
and the Library of Congress and
possibly many other libraries

00:04:47.960 --> 00:04:51.530
about this collection and
what we can do with this

00:04:51.530 --> 00:04:57.810
and similar collections that
we have in our institutions.

00:04:57.810 --> 00:05:02.330
So this all started -- this
collection has a very long history

00:05:02.330 --> 00:05:05.340
and I'll tell you a little
bit about in a few minutes.

00:05:05.340 --> 00:05:09.560
And my history with this
connection is very, very recent.

00:05:09.560 --> 00:05:18.580
A year ago or slightly more than a
year ago I got an e-mail from Hamid

00:05:18.580 --> 00:05:23.890
and Waleed from the British
Library and he asked me

00:05:23.890 --> 00:05:28.540
about do you know something
about the books that NYU received

00:05:28.540 --> 00:05:30.690
from Abdulhamid the Second.

00:05:30.690 --> 00:05:34.220
And I hadn't heard
about these books,

00:05:34.220 --> 00:05:40.260
I mean I'm monotonous I did
my PhD at NYU, no one told me

00:05:40.260 --> 00:05:42.240
about these things, I didn't know.

00:05:42.240 --> 00:05:49.680
And so I contacted our
university archivist, Janet Bunde.

00:05:49.680 --> 00:05:54.950
In general, I should say that
this is a collaborative project

00:05:54.950 --> 00:05:59.850
with the university archives at
NYU and the special collections.

00:05:59.850 --> 00:06:03.650
So I should mention my colleagues
Janet Bunde from the archives

00:06:03.650 --> 00:06:06.660
and Charlotte Priddle from
the special collections.

00:06:06.660 --> 00:06:11.140
They've all been extremely
supportive and helpful and in fact,

00:06:11.140 --> 00:06:13.040
instrumental in this project.

00:06:13.040 --> 00:06:17.750
So I contact Janet and ask her do
you know nothing about these books

00:06:17.750 --> 00:06:19.590
or do you know anything
about these gifts?

00:06:19.590 --> 00:06:21.840
Are there documents in the archive?

00:06:21.840 --> 00:06:24.960
And a few days later she
came back and said yes,

00:06:24.960 --> 00:06:27.490
actually we have things
in the accession books

00:06:27.490 --> 00:06:29.090
and these are accession books

00:06:29.090 --> 00:06:31.620
and these are the entries
in the accession books.

00:06:31.620 --> 00:06:36.210
And at that time we thought
-- we just assumed okay,

00:06:36.210 --> 00:06:39.420
we have the accession books, we
know that we received the books,

00:06:39.420 --> 00:06:44.780
but we probably lost them
in one of the renovations

00:06:46.010 --> 00:06:48.480
since the 19th century,
the late 19th century

00:06:48.480 --> 00:06:53.200
when we received the books.

00:06:53.200 --> 00:06:59.200
So we just -- but we also
found from the accession books

00:06:59.200 --> 00:07:01.710
that we received the books
through Abram Hewitt.

00:07:01.710 --> 00:07:05.360
So basically, there are two
main protagonists to this story.

00:07:05.360 --> 00:07:07.870
One is obviously of
Abdulhamid the Second

00:07:07.870 --> 00:07:12.530
and perhaps the most famous
sultan of the 19 century,

00:07:12.530 --> 00:07:15.580
definitely the second
half of the 19th century.

00:07:15.580 --> 00:07:17.680
And the second was Abram S. Hewitt.

00:07:17.680 --> 00:07:20.220
At the time he was
the representative

00:07:20.220 --> 00:07:24.570
and New York's representative
to the house.

00:07:24.570 --> 00:07:27.020
And later he became
the mayor of New York.

00:07:27.020 --> 00:07:29.590
Apparently at that
time Abdulhamid thought

00:07:29.590 --> 00:07:35.270
that he would become the
President of the United States,

00:07:35.270 --> 00:07:37.190
what actually did not happen.

00:07:37.190 --> 00:07:46.420
But in 1884 Hewitt visited
Istanbul and had several meetings

00:07:46.420 --> 00:07:48.930
with Abdulhamid the Second.

00:07:48.930 --> 00:07:55.040
And in one of these meetings Hewitt
presented with this collection,

00:07:55.040 --> 00:07:59.650
with the collection that
the Library of Congress have

00:07:59.650 --> 00:08:05.350
and the collection that we have.

00:08:05.350 --> 00:08:12.630
Interestingly, in 1940 Hewitt's
son wrote a very interesting piece

00:08:12.630 --> 00:08:16.920
for the New Yorker and I'm
also grateful for Janet

00:08:16.920 --> 00:08:19.280
for pointing this out to me.

00:08:19.280 --> 00:08:24.030
And the piece is titled
The Sultan's Gift

00:08:24.030 --> 00:08:26.650
and this is the piece
from the New Yorker.

00:08:26.650 --> 00:08:29.900
And it actually tells some
very interesting stories,

00:08:29.900 --> 00:08:33.490
very interesting details
about this collection.

00:08:33.490 --> 00:08:39.210
And we hear the numbers
and Hewitt's son says

00:08:39.210 --> 00:08:45.900
that his father received 395
books from Abdulhamid the Second.

00:08:45.900 --> 00:08:48.410
He also says that when
Hewitt came back

00:08:48.410 --> 00:08:54.400
to the US he sent Abdulhamid
some gilded pens

00:08:54.400 --> 00:08:57.850
and 10,000 Virginia cigarettes.

00:08:57.850 --> 00:08:59.180
So it's a very cool piece

00:08:59.180 --> 00:09:03.070 position:56%
if you have time you should actually
take the time and take a look at it.

00:09:03.070 --> 00:09:09.030
But so that was the
first clue we had.

00:09:09.030 --> 00:09:14.310
Then a few days ago, less
than a week ago actually,

00:09:14.310 --> 00:09:17.580
Professor [inaudible]
from Boston University

00:09:17.580 --> 00:09:24.870
who actually has seen the set
at NYU sent me this document.

00:09:24.870 --> 00:09:30.120
This is a document from the Ottoman
archives talking about the gift.

00:09:30.120 --> 00:09:38.570
It was issued by the [inaudible],
the Ministry of Education

00:09:38.570 --> 00:09:40.480
or something along those lines.

00:09:40.480 --> 00:09:43.510
And what is interesting
in this story --

00:09:43.510 --> 00:09:46.450
from this document is that it
completely changed my perception,

00:09:46.450 --> 00:09:50.540
not completely, but it changed my
perception of history of the gift.

00:09:50.540 --> 00:09:57.450 position:56%
Before I saw this document I assumed
that Hewitt received one set,

00:09:57.450 --> 00:10:01.480
gave it to the Library of Congress
and then Abdulhamid was so excited

00:10:01.480 --> 00:10:06.410
by the reception or
by the enthusiasm

00:10:06.410 --> 00:10:12.930
that he gave Hewitt a second set.

00:10:12.930 --> 00:10:15.920
And for some reason apparently
because he didn't want

00:10:15.920 --> 00:10:20.610
to pay taxes he gave
this collection to NYU.

00:10:20.610 --> 00:10:22.680
But this document tells
a very different story.

00:10:22.680 --> 00:10:28.990
This document apparently Hewitt
was presented with two sets,

00:10:28.990 --> 00:10:35.930 position:56%
one from what they call the American
[inaudible] that is the Library

00:10:35.930 --> 00:10:40.200
of Congress and the second
was a personal set or a set

00:10:40.200 --> 00:10:47.810
that was intended to be or to be a
personal set for Monsieur Hewitt.

00:10:47.810 --> 00:10:53.190
It actually describes
what you Abdulhamid wanted

00:10:53.190 --> 00:10:54.490
to do with the books.

00:10:54.490 --> 00:10:59.010
He specifically explains
how they should be bound

00:10:59.010 --> 00:11:01.270
and how they should be inscribed.

00:11:01.270 --> 00:11:04.010
He also said -- we also learned

00:11:04.010 --> 00:11:09.570
from this document the
scope of this collection.

00:11:09.570 --> 00:11:13.600
Basically, it's the connection
should include all the books

00:11:13.600 --> 00:11:19.760
that were published presumably
in Istanbul or in the core lands

00:11:19.760 --> 00:11:28.950
of the empire from Abdulhamid's
accession to the throne in 1876.

00:11:28.950 --> 00:11:32.520
There are two copies
of this document.

00:11:32.520 --> 00:11:38.960
This is one, this is the second
and they were issued in 1884,

00:11:38.960 --> 00:11:46.530
the same date when the books
were actually given to Hewitt.

00:11:46.530 --> 00:11:51.610
So this is how the books look
like and one of the things

00:11:51.610 --> 00:11:56.990
that is actually interesting
about the NYU set is

00:11:56.990 --> 00:11:59.190 position:56%
that it remained pretty much intact.

00:11:59.190 --> 00:12:04.150
I mean some books are in
better shapes than others.

00:12:04.150 --> 00:12:09.790 position:56%
But we still have the physical books
bound and I think that the Library

00:12:09.790 --> 00:12:14.250
of Congress have two or three
books that remained intact.

00:12:14.250 --> 00:12:17.340
But we still have the
physical object

00:12:17.340 --> 00:12:24.390
and they are extremely brittle and
the paper is incredibly acidic,

00:12:24.390 --> 00:12:28.790
especially the books
published in Arabic.

00:12:28.790 --> 00:12:34.640
I don't know why were
printed on a much better paper

00:12:34.640 --> 00:12:40.440
and I don't have a good
explanation why this is the case,

00:12:40.440 --> 00:12:45.440
but this is how it is.

00:12:45.440 --> 00:12:48.700
And so among the -- so, so far

00:12:48.700 --> 00:12:55.310 position:56%
at NYU we have catalogued mostly the
Turkish or the Ottoman Turkish part

00:12:55.310 --> 00:12:59.210
and we are about or we
just started working

00:12:59.210 --> 00:13:02.690
on the Persian and the Arabic.

00:13:02.690 --> 00:13:07.890
And most of the collection out
of the 400 titles in our books

00:13:07.890 --> 00:13:12.260
in Ottoman and the rest are
in Persian and in Arabic.

00:13:12.260 --> 00:13:19.110 position:56%
So for the Ottoman collection you
can find books by the usual suspects

00:13:19.110 --> 00:13:21.530
or what I call the usual suspects.

00:13:21.530 --> 00:13:27.700
Books by Ahmed Cevdet Pasha,
the famous jurist and scholar

00:13:27.700 --> 00:13:31.910
and also a Ministry of Justice

00:13:31.910 --> 00:13:38.420
and an incredibly important
reformer of the 19th century.

00:13:38.420 --> 00:13:42.080
So we have most of his
works in this collection,

00:13:42.080 --> 00:13:45.740
including the recently published
the Mecelle, [inaudible],

00:13:45.740 --> 00:13:55.680
the Ottoman Legal Code published
in the mid 60's or the late 60's.

00:13:55.680 --> 00:13:59.880
There are also books by Ahmed
Midhat Efendi, the famous author

00:13:59.880 --> 00:14:05.650
and novelist of the
19th century who was one

00:14:05.650 --> 00:14:08.070
of his works was recently
published --

00:14:08.070 --> 00:14:10.560
a translation of one of his work
was recently published in English.

00:14:10.560 --> 00:14:17.190
So this is how a book by
Midhat Efendi looks like.

00:14:17.190 --> 00:14:18.490
What is interesting
about these books

00:14:18.490 --> 00:14:23.590
and this actually raises some
questions, cataloguing questions

00:14:23.590 --> 00:14:26.690 position:56%
because the books, the
collection, what is very interesting

00:14:26.690 --> 00:14:30.790
about the collection even if
the books are well-known is

00:14:30.790 --> 00:14:33.410
that it raises some interesting
questions about the book,

00:14:33.410 --> 00:14:37.830
the history of the book in
the early Hamidian period.

00:14:37.830 --> 00:14:43.540
And some of the questions that
we are confronted when we see,

00:14:43.540 --> 00:14:47.930
I mean those title pages raise
some very interesting questions

00:14:47.930 --> 00:14:49.260
in terms of cataloguing.

00:14:49.260 --> 00:14:53.970
So for instance, there was
this very interesting practice

00:14:53.970 --> 00:14:58.430
that you had the publisher,
but then or a printer,

00:14:58.430 --> 00:15:01.180
but then a publisher
bought the printed books

00:15:01.180 --> 00:15:03.290
and just stamped them like this.

00:15:03.290 --> 00:15:06.580
So it's not part of the title page

00:15:06.580 --> 00:15:12.250
and for most part most
records have tended

00:15:12.250 --> 00:15:15.750
to take the printer
as the publisher.

00:15:15.750 --> 00:15:21.840
But there we have this interesting
practice and they're all kind

00:15:21.840 --> 00:15:25.460
of practices that we see when we
look at this collection closely.

00:15:25.460 --> 00:15:32.340
And because I'm not an expert
in Hamidian book history,

00:15:32.340 --> 00:15:38.320
so I still don't know what to
do with these practices and how

00:15:38.320 --> 00:15:41.330
to reflect them in our records.

00:15:41.330 --> 00:15:45.110
But I just thought it would be
interesting to point this out.

00:15:45.110 --> 00:15:50.410
There are also quite a few
translations from a wide range

00:15:50.410 --> 00:15:58.720
of languages from Russian to
French to English and German.

00:15:58.720 --> 00:16:05.080
This is a translation of
Alexandre Dumas [inaudible],

00:16:05.080 --> 00:16:10.130
but we have a very wide range
of books, mostly novels,

00:16:10.130 --> 00:16:16.830
but also military manuals published
in the early Hamidian period.

00:16:17.940 --> 00:16:19.790
There are also quite
a few lithographs.

00:16:19.790 --> 00:16:24.130
Most of the books are movable and
were printed using movable type,

00:16:24.130 --> 00:16:25.650
but there are quite
a few lithographs.

00:16:25.650 --> 00:16:28.580
And what is interesting
about those lithographs is

00:16:28.580 --> 00:16:31.560
that they are usually books
that are almost ephemera.

00:16:31.560 --> 00:16:39.200
They are textbooks, they
are manuals for engineers

00:16:39.200 --> 00:16:43.360
and railroad builders
and all those things.

00:16:43.360 --> 00:16:48.070 position:56%
And I should say that this it's nice

00:16:48.070 --> 00:16:50.540
because it supplements
a very nice collection

00:16:50.540 --> 00:16:54.380
of lithographs that we have at NYU.

00:16:54.380 --> 00:16:57.040
And covering lithographs
basically from the [inaudible]

00:16:57.040 --> 00:16:58.840
to the Indian subcontinent.

00:16:58.840 --> 00:17:05.530
So this collection fills
a very interesting gap

00:17:05.530 --> 00:17:09.920
that we have in our collection.

00:17:09.920 --> 00:17:13.310
But the most interesting thing

00:17:13.310 --> 00:17:19.020
about the collection is
not the famous works.

00:17:19.020 --> 00:17:22.570
One of the interesting things
and it was a bit puzzling

00:17:22.570 --> 00:17:27.240
when we started going through the
boxes is that we realized that most

00:17:27.240 --> 00:17:30.720
of the collection or not most,
but there are quite a few titles

00:17:30.720 --> 00:17:32.470
that are almost ephemera.

00:17:32.470 --> 00:17:39.640
And this one for example is a
very small book that was done

00:17:39.640 --> 00:17:46.940
for the commanders of small
military units in the Hamidian Army

00:17:46.940 --> 00:17:48.770
or the Hamidian Military.

00:17:48.770 --> 00:17:56.620
There are also all kind of annual
statistics of the court system,

00:17:56.620 --> 00:18:02.200
cookbooks, there are textbooks
intended for different students

00:18:02.200 --> 00:18:09.760
in different stages of the
Ottoman or the Hamidian curriculum.

00:18:09.760 --> 00:18:19.140
And I think that there are the
most interesting and rare books

00:18:19.140 --> 00:18:20.480
that we got for this collection.

00:18:20.480 --> 00:18:28.620
And these things have not been --
obviously, they were not purchased

00:18:28.620 --> 00:18:33.670 position:56%
in the 19th century and if they were
they were never taken seriously.

00:18:33.670 --> 00:18:36.640
So it's a way of getting very --

00:18:36.640 --> 00:18:45.570
it offers a glimpse into
the less prestigious sides

00:18:45.570 --> 00:18:49.600
of the Hamidian book
culture of the first,

00:18:49.600 --> 00:18:53.980
at least for the first
decade of Abdulhamid's rule.

00:18:55.340 --> 00:19:01.910
So and this is the most interesting
thing for this talk I think.

